VALUES
(1, 36, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'Timna was concubine to Eliphaz Esau’s son', 4, 45, 'connection', 'Concubines in Scripture', 'The mention of Timna as a concubine highlights the cultural practice of concubinage in the ancient Near East. This practice is referenced elsewhere, such as in Genesis 30:3, where Bilhah serves as a concubine to Jacob. Understanding this context helps illuminate the family dynamics and social structures of the time, emphasizing how these relationships were integral to lineage and inheritance.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:3", "description": "Bilhah as Jacob''s concubine"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'she bare to Eliphaz Amalek', 51, 77, 'theology', 'Identity of Amalek', 'Many scholars believe that Amalek symbolizes opposition to God’s people, as seen in later biblical accounts (Exodus 17:8-16). The descendants of Amalek would become significant adversaries of Israel, thus establishing a theme of conflict between the faithful and those who oppose God’s purposes. This relationship underscores the importance of lineage in understanding biblical narratives of conflict and divine justice.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Exodus 17:8-16", "description": "Conflict between Israel and Amalek"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 12, 12, 'kjv', 'these were the sons of Adah Esau’s wife', 79, 118, 'question', 'Significance of Adah', 'What can we learn about the role of women like Adah in the biblical narrative, particularly in relation to their influence on the next generation? Considering that her sons play a significant role in the unfolding story of Israel, how might this reflect on the value and impact of family heritage in our faith journeys today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'the sons of Reuel', 14, 31, 'connection', 'Reuel''s Significance', 'Reuel, the son of Esau, is an important figure in the genealogy of Esau’s descendants. His descendants are mentioned later in Scripture, particularly in Exodus 2:16, where he is referred to as Jethro, the priest of Midian, showing the continuation of his line. This connection emphasizes the intertwining of the Israelite and Midianite cultures, and highlights God''s plan to use diverse backgrounds for His purposes.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 2:16", "description": "Reuel is identified as Jethro, a key figure in Moses'' life."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 10:29", "description": "Moses'' relationship with Hobab, Reuel''s son, highlights the importance of this lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Nahath, and Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah', 33, 71, 'theology', 'The Importance of Names', 'The names of Reuel''s sons carry significant meanings in the Hebrew tradition, reflecting attributes of God''s character or the circumstances surrounding their birth. Understanding the meanings of these names can enrich our understanding of God''s covenant with Esau''s lineage, suggesting that God''s purpose can extend beyond Israel alone. Many scholars believe that the diverse names indicate a broader theological theme of God''s redemptive plan encompassing all nations.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'these were the sons of Bashemath Esau’s wife', 73, 117, 'question', 'Understanding Family Dynamics', 'What does the mention of Bashemath as Esau''s wife reveal about the relationships and alliances in Esau''s family? How do these familial connections influence the narrative of the descendants of Esau and their interactions with Israel? Reflecting on this can provide insights into the importance of family lineage and its impact on identity within the biblical narrative.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Aholibamah, the daughter of Anah', 27, 59, 'connection', 'Connection to Esau''s Lineage', 'Aholibamah is an important figure in the lineage of Esau, highlighting the intermarriages that shaped the Edomite people. This connects to Genesis 26:34-35, where Esau''s choice of wives is noted to have caused grief to Isaac and Rebekah. Understanding these relationships and their implications helps in comprehending the broader narrative of the patriarchs and their descendants.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 26:34-35", "description": "Esau''s marriages and their impact on his family dynamics."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'the daughter of Anah', 39, 59, 'theology', 'Covenantal Implications', 'The mention of Aholibamah, as the daughter of Anah, suggests the importance of lineage and covenant in the biblical narrative. Many scholars believe this reflects God''s ongoing purpose in preserving a chosen line through which His promises will be fulfilled, as seen throughout Scripture, particularly in the context of genealogies. This passage underscores the significance of familial ties in God''s redemptive history.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the theological implications of genealogies in the Old Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'Esau’s wife: and she bare to Esau Jeush, and Jaalam, and Korah.', 84, 147, 'question', 'Understanding God’s Plan', 'What does it signify that Aholibamah bore these sons to Esau, particularly in the context of God''s covenant with Abraham? Reflecting on their names and roles in the unfolding narrative might reveal deeper insights into God''s plan for Israel and Edom. How do these familial connections impact your understanding of God''s faithfulness across generations?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'These were dukes of the sons of Esau', 0, 36, 'connection', 'Esau''s Lineage Significance', 'The mention of Esau''s sons as dukes highlights the fulfillment of God''s promise to Abraham concerning the nations that would come from him (Genesis 17:4-6). Esau''s descendants becoming dukes in Edom reflects a significant development in the history of Israel''s neighbors and their relationships. This lineage enriches the understanding of the broader narrative of God''s covenant with Abraham and the complexities of familial ties.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 17:4-6", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham about descendants."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'the sons of Eliphaz the firstborn son of Esau', 38, 83, 'theology', 'Firstborn Rights and Blessings', 'Many scholars believe that the emphasis on Eliphaz being the firstborn son of Esau highlights the significance of firstborn rights and blessings within ancient Near Eastern culture. The firstborn typically received a double portion of inheritance and leadership, which plays a vital role in the unfolding narrative of the Israelites and their relationship with Edom. This illustrates the dynamics of blessing and challenge between the two nations.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 25:29-34", "description": "Esau selling his birthright."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'duke Teman, duke Omar, duke Zepho, duke Kenaz', 85, 130, 'question', 'Understanding Leadership in Edom', 'What does the title ''duke'' signify about the governance and social structure in Edom? How might the leadership of these figures reflect God''s sovereignty in establishing nations? Consider how this structure compares to Israel''s leadership under God''s covenant.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Duke Korah, duke Gatam, and duke Amalek', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Lineage of Amalek', 'The mention of ''duke Amalek'' is significant as it connects to the later conflict between the Israelites and the Amalekites, detailed in Exodus 17:8-16. This conflict symbolizes the ongoing struggle between God''s people and opposition. Understanding Amalek''s lineage helps frame the historical enmity that developed, reinforcing the thematic conflict present in Scripture.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 17:8", "description": "The first mention of the Amalekites attacking Israel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'these are the dukes that came of Eliphaz', 41, 81, 'theology', 'Importance of Leadership', 'The phrase ''these are the dukes'' emphasizes the significance of leadership roles within the Edomite society descended from Esau. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical theme of lineage and authority, suggesting that God’s plans encompass not only Israel but also neighboring nations, illustrating His sovereignty over all peoples.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the implications of leadership in biblical narratives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'duke Gatam, and duke Amalek', 12, 39, 'question', 'Understanding Legacy', 'What does it mean for us today that these individuals are recognized as dukes? How might the legacies of leaders affect their descendants and communities, both positively and negatively?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'these were the sons of Adah', 103, 130, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Sons''', '''בנים (banim, H1121) - sons, children; this Hebrew term often conveys more than just biological offspring, indicating a broader sense of heritage and identity. The use of ''sons'' here highlights the importance of family and continuity in the narrative of Genesis.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1121", "description": "Strong''s number for ''sons'' in the Old Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'the sons of Reuel Esau’s son', 14, 42, 'connection', 'Connection to Esau''s Lineage', 'The mention of Reuel, Esau''s son, connects to Genesis 25:25, where Esau''s birthright and lineage are introduced. Understanding this lineage is crucial as it sets the stage for the development of the Edomite nation, which plays a significant role throughout the Old Testament. The dynamics between the descendants of Jacob and Esau illustrate broader themes of conflict and reconciliation in biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 25:25", "description": "Introduction of Esau and his significance in biblical genealogy."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'duke Nahath, duke Zerah, duke Shammah, duke Mizzah', 44, 94, 'theology', 'Noble Titles and Leadership', 'The term ''duke'' signifies a position of leadership and authority within ancient societies. This suggests that God''s covenant promises extend not only to Jacob but also to Esau''s descendants, emphasizing that God''s plans encompass all nations. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical theme that God''s sovereignty operates beyond human expectations, including those who are not part of the direct covenant community.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'these are the sons of Bashemath Esau’s wife', 156, 199, 'question', 'Significance of Family Ties', 'What might the inclusion of Bashemath''s sons reveal about the importance of family heritage in God''s narrative? This passage encourages reflection on how our familial connections shape our identity and purpose within God''s plan.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'these are the dukes that came of Reuel', 96, 134, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Duke''', 'While this passage is primarily in Hebrew, the concept of ''duke'' translates to similar terms in Greek, such as ''ἄρχων'' (archon, G758) - ruler, leader, or chief. This indicates a position of authority and governance, highlighting the organizational structure of Esau''s descendants and their role in the region of Edom.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G758", "description": "Greek term for ruler, significant in understanding leadership roles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'duke Jeush, duke Jaalam, duke Korah', 50, 85, 'connection', 'Dukes of Edom Connection', 'The names mentioned here, particularly ''Korah'', can be linked to Numbers 16:1-3, where Korah leads a rebellion against Moses. This connection highlights the significant role these descendants played in Israel''s history and serves as a reminder of the themes of leadership and rebellion within God''s chosen people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Numbers 16:1", "description": "Korah''s rebellion against Moses"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'Aholibamah Esau’s wife', 26, 48, 'theology', 'Marriage and Lineage', 'The mention of Aholibamah as Esau''s wife underscores the importance of family lineage in the biblical narrative. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader theological theme of God''s covenant through specific lineages, showing how God works through families to fulfill His promises, particularly in the context of the Abrahamic covenant.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 17:7", "description": "God''s covenant with Abraham and his descendants"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'duke Korah', 75, 85, 'greek', 'Significance of ''Korah''', 'As a name, ''Korah'' (H7141) implies ''baldness'' or ''shaved''. This term may symbolize a state of humility or even disgrace, as baldness was sometimes associated with mourning in the ancient Near Eastern culture. Understanding the meaning of the name can provide deeper insight into the character and legacy of those who bore it.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7141", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Korah"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'these were the dukes that came of Aholibamah', 87, 131, 'question', 'Understanding Dukes'' Authority', 'What does it mean for ''dukes'' to come from Aholibamah in the context of leadership and authority in Edom? Considering the significance of lineage and leadership roles, how does this shape our understanding of God''s purpose for families and their influence within communities?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Esau, who is Edom, and these are their dukes.', 0, 67, 'connection', 'Esau and Edom Connection', 'The identification of Esau as Edom is significant in understanding the historical context of Israel’s relationship with Edom. This connection is reinforced in Obadiah 1:10, which highlights the enmity between the two nations. Understanding this familial link helps to frame the struggles depicted throughout the history of Israel and Edom, showcasing God''s overarching plan for His people amidst their conflicts.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Obadiah 1:10", "description": "Obadiah discusses the judgment against Edom for its violence against Jacob."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Esau, who is Edom, and these are their dukes.', 0, 67, 'theology', 'Identity and Heritage', 'This passage illustrates the importance of identity and heritage in the biblical narrative. Many scholars believe that the designation of Esau as Edom emphasizes the significance of lineage in God''s plan, showing how nations derive their identity from their patriarchs. This notion resonates with the New Testament teaching on spiritual lineage through Christ, as seen in Romans 9:6-8, affirming that true descendants are those of faith.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Romans 9:6-8", "description": "Paul discusses spiritual lineage in the context of God''s promises."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Esau, who is Edom, and these are their dukes.', 0, 67, 'question', 'Personal Identity Reflection', 'What does it mean for us today to understand our identity in relation to our spiritual heritage? As Esau is identified with Edom, how does our identity in Christ shape our lives and influence our relationships with others?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Esau, who is Edom, and these are their dukes.', 0, 67, 'greek', 'Significance of Duke', 'דּוּקָא (duka, H1786) - duke, leader, chief. This term indicates a position of authority and governance, underscoring the political structure of Edomite society and the importance of leadership in the fulfillment of God''s plans.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1786", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term related to leadership."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Seir the Horite, who inhabited the land;', 0, 62, 'connection', 'Connection to Genesis 14:6', 'This mention of Seir the Horite ties back to the broader narrative of the land of Canaan and the people inhabiting it. In Genesis 14:6, the Horites are noted as living in the mountains of Seir, which emphasizes the geographical and historical significance of this region in biblical history. Understanding these connections helps us appreciate the context of Israel''s later conquests.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 14:6", "description": "The Horites mentioned in the context of Canaan''s inhabitants."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Lotan, and Shobal, and Zibeon, and Anah,', 63, 103, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'The names of Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, and Anah may reflect various attributes of their lineage and roles in the community. Many scholars believe that names in the Hebrew Bible often carry meanings that reveal character traits or divine purposes. This suggests a theological understanding that God is involved in the lives of these individuals and their descendants.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'who inhabited the land;', 39, 62, 'question', 'Reflection on Inhabitation', 'What does it mean for a people to ''inhabit'' a land in the context of God''s promise to Abraham? How does this idea of inheritance and belonging shape our understanding of God''s covenant with Israel?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'These are the sons of Seir the Horite,', 0, 38, 'greek', 'Hebrew Lexicon Insight', 'Horite (חֹרִי, H2732) - a term referring to a group of mountain dwellers in Edom, indicating their cultural and geographical identity. Understanding this term reveals insights into the ethnic diversity present in the region during biblical times.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H2732", "description": "Strong''s number for the term Horite."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Dishon, and Ezer, and Dishan', 4, 32, 'connection', 'Esau''s Lineage', 'The names Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan appear in a genealogical context, mirroring other genealogies in the Bible such as those found in Genesis 10:15-18. This connection highlights the importance of lineage in biblical narratives, particularly regarding the Edomites'' claim to land and identity. Understanding these relationships helps to clarify the historical and cultural context of Israel''s neighbors.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:15-18", "description": "Genealogy of the Canaanite nations"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'of the Horites', 54, 68, 'theology', 'Edom''s Leadership Structure', 'This passage emphasizes the authority of the Horites and their dukes in Edom, suggesting a significant level of organization and governance among these tribes. Many scholars believe that this reflects God''s providential ordering of nations, illustrating His sovereign plan in establishing nations and their boundaries (Acts 17:26). This understanding encourages believers to recognize God''s hand in history and national identities.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Acts 17:26", "description": "God''s sovereignty over nations"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'children of Seir', 74, 90, 'question', 'Identity and Heritage', 'What does it mean to be referred to as the ''children of Seir'' in this context? How does this description of descent shape our understanding of identity in terms of heritage and relationship with God? Reflecting on our own identities as children of God, how might this influence our actions and relationships with others?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'And the children of Lotan were Hori and Hemam;', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Children of Lotan', 'The mention of Lotan''s children, Hori and Hemam, connects to the broader narrative of Genesis where lineage and heritage play a crucial role. For instance, Genesis 10:15-18 details the descendants of Canaan, underscoring the significance of family lines. Understanding these connections helps illuminate the geography and relationships among ancient peoples.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:15-18", "description": "Describes the descendants of Canaan, showing the importance of lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'and Lotan’s sister was Timna.', 47, 76, 'theology', 'Role of Women in Genealogy', 'This verse introduces Timna, Lotan''s sister, highlighting the often-overlooked role of women in biblical genealogies. Many scholars believe that while genealogies typically focus on male lineage, the inclusion of women like Timna demonstrates their importance in family and societal structures, reflecting God''s acknowledgment of all individuals in His plan.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the significance of women in biblical genealogies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Lotan’s sister was Timna.', 51, 76, 'question', 'Understanding Timna''s Role', 'What can we learn about the significance of family relationships from the mention of Timna as Lotan''s sister? How might her presence in this lineage inform our understanding of community and support in biblical narratives?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the children of Shobal were these; Alvan, and Manahath, and Ebal, Shepho, and Onam.', 0, 87, 'connection', 'Lineage of Edom', 'This verse lists the descendants of Shobal, a significant figure in the lineage of Edom. This connects to 1 Chronicles 1:40-42, which also details the descendants of Esau. Understanding these genealogies helps illustrate the broader narrative of the Edomite people and their relationship with Israel, emphasizing God''s plan through familial lines.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Chronicles 1:40-42", "description": "Details of Edomite genealogy"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'children of Shobal', 8, 26, 'theology', 'Significance of Lineage', 'Many scholars believe that genealogies in Scripture serve to highlight God''s faithfulness across generations, showing how His purposes are fulfilled through specific families. The mention of Shobal''s children underscores the idea that God''s covenant extends beyond Israel, encompassing all nations, as seen in the broader context of Genesis.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Ebal', 64, 68, 'greek', 'Ebal and Blessings', 'אֵבַל (Ebal, H11) - a hill in Israel, signifies the place of curses and blessings in Deuteronomy 27. The connection of the name Ebal to the children of Shobal may reflect the significance of this name in the broader narrative of God''s covenant with His people, highlighting themes of blessing and judgment.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H11", "description": "Strong''s number for Ebal"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'children of Shobal', 8, 26, 'question', 'Reflection on Heritage', 'What does it mean for us today to be part of a spiritual lineage, as shown by the children of Shobal? How can understanding our spiritual heritage influence our identity and purpose within the body of Christ?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'this was that Anah that found the mules in the wilderness', 59, 116, 'connection', 'Connection to Wilderness Experiences', 'The mention of Anah finding mules in the wilderness can be cross-referenced with Exodus 16:2-3, where the Israelites faced hardships in the wilderness and longed for the comforts of Egypt. This connection highlights that wilderness experiences can lead to important discoveries and growth, both for individuals and communities. Just as Anah''s discovery was notable, the Israelites'' time in the wilderness ultimately shaped their identity as God''s chosen people.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 16:2-3", "description": "Israelites'' wilderness experience and longing for Egypt."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'found the mules in the wilderness', 83, 116, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Discovery', 'This passage suggests that God''s providence operates even in the most unexpected circumstances. The discovery of the mules in the wilderness reflects a broader theological theme of God providing for needs in times of uncertainty. Many scholars believe this foreshadows how God will provide for His people in their own wilderness experiences throughout Scripture, culminating in the provision of Christ as the Good Shepherd.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses God''s providence in the lives of individuals."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Zibeon; both Ajah, and Anah', 30, 57, 'question', 'Significance of Family Heritage', 'What does it mean for us today to recognize the family heritage of Zibeon and his sons? Consider how our backgrounds and family influences shape our identity and responsibilities. In what ways can acknowledging our heritage inspire us to fulfill our roles in our communities and before God?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'the children of Anah were these', 4, 35, 'connection', 'Lineage Significance', 'This phrase highlights the importance of genealogies in biblical narrative, connecting Anah''s descendants to the broader story of the Edomites. For further context, see 1 Chronicles 1:38, where Anah is also mentioned, emphasizing the continuity of family lines in the biblical history.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "1 Chronicles 1:38", "description": "This verse includes Anah in a genealogical list, showing his significance."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 36, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'Aholibamah the daughter of Anah', 49, 80, 'theology', 'Role of Women in Genealogy', 'The inclusion of Aholibamah here suggests a theological emphasis on the roles women play in God''s unfolding plan, as genealogies traditionally focus on male descendants. This may reflect God''s inclusive view of family and heritage, which is further supported in Galatians 3:28, where Paul emphasizes the equality of all believers.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 3:28", "description": "This verse underscores equality in Christ, relevant to the inclusion of women in genealogies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
